President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has proclaimed October 2022 as National Arts and Humanities Month in the United States. The proclamation recognizes the importance of arts and humanities in American society and highlights the administration's commitment to making them more accessible. The government has invested significant funds in organizations such as the National Endowment for the Arts and the National Endowment for the Humanities, and additional support has been allocated to help cultural institutions recover from the pandemic. The President's recent Executive Order promotes the arts, humanities, and museum and library services, emphasizing their role in strengthening the nation's health, economy, equity, and civic life. The order also re-establishes the President's Committee on the Arts and Humanities and appoints diverse leaders to head these agencies. The proclamation encourages the American people to observe National Arts and Humanities Month through appropriate programs, ceremonies, and celebrations, recognizing that democracy requires wisdom and that these disciplines foster understanding and inspire progress.